This article is part of my SOLID Principles in Angular series, where I break down each SOLID principle from an Angular engineer’s perspective using practical examples and real-world Angular scenarios.
In this article, we’ll focus on the Open/Closed Principle (OCP).
Like the other SOLID principles, this one is simple to understand in theory, but applying it consistently in real-world applications requires experience and thoughtful design.
When used correctly, OCP helps us build Angular applications that are easier to maintain, scale, and evolve as business requirements grow. It’s time to break it down and see how it applies to modern Angular development.
What does the Open/Closed Principle say?
Software entities should be open for extension, but closed for modification.
In simple terms:
You should be able to add new behavior without modifying existing working code.
This becomes very important in enterprise systems. Why? Because modifying stable code introduces risk. Let’s analyze it with some examples.
Bad Example
Imagine you want to implement the payment process in your project. The first thing that comes to your mind is something like the code below:
class PaymentProcessor {
process(type: string) {
if (type === 'paypal') {}
if (type === 'stripe') {}
}
}This code looks fine initially, but after a while, the business says Add Apple Pay as well. Now you must modify the existing class as below!
class PaymentService {
processPayment(method: string) {
if (method === 'paypal') {
console.log('Pay via PayPal');
} else if (method === 'stripe') {
console.log('Pay via Stripe');
} else if (method === 'applepay') {
console.log('Pay via Apple Pay');
}
}
}This way, with every new payment provider that you are supposed to add to your code, you need to change the working code that violates OCP though you can overcome to this fault by better design using Abstraction! Let’s improve the above example. First, let’s define an abstraction.
interface PaymentMethod {
pay(): void;
}Now let’s create implementations.
class PaypalPayment implements PaymentMethod {
pay() {}
}class StripePayment implements PaymentMethod {
pay() {}
}Now we can extend behavior by adding new implementations. As you noticed, there is no need to modify existing logic, and it’s much better now.
OCP in Angular with Dependency Injection
Angular’s dependency injection system makes OCP much easier to implement. Let’s use a more realistic example.
Step 1: Define abstraction.
interface PaymentProvider {
pay(amount: number): void;
}Step 2: Create implementations.
@Injectable()
class PaypalService implements PaymentProvider {
pay(amount: number) {
console.log(`PayPal payment: ${amount}`);
}
}@Injectable()
class StripeService implements PaymentProvider {
pay(amount: number) {
console.log(`Stripe payment: ${amount}`);
}
}Step 3: Inject dependency.
@Component({})
class CheckoutComponent {
constructor(private paymentProvider: PaymentProvider) {} checkout() {
this.paymentProvider.pay(100);
}
}
Now the component doesn’t care whether payment happens via:

• PayPal

• Stripe

• Apple Pay
It only cares about this:
paymentProvider.pay()That’s exactly what good abstraction looks like. It’s awkward, right? cause we need to know how Angular DI helps us to resolve the dependencies! Let’s dive into it then!
How Angular DI Helps
It’s easy, indeed, Angular decides which implementation to inject; let me show you an example:
providers: [
{ provide: PaymentProvider, useClass: PaypalService }
]Now let’s suppose the business says Use Stripe instead. You only need to change the provider configuration.
providers: [
{ provide: PaymentProvider, useClass: StripeService }
]The component stays unchanged. That’s OCP in practice. Let’s add a new feature (Apple Pay).
Need Apple Pay? Just add a new implementation.
@Injectable()
class ApplePayService implements PaymentProvider {
pay(amount: number) {
console.log(`Apple Pay payment: ${amount}`);
}
}Update provider:
providers: [
{ provide: PaymentProvider, useClass: ApplePayService }
]Done. No component changes required. This is one of Angular’s biggest architectural strengths.
That’s it for this article. I hope this gave you a practical understanding of how the Open/Closed Principle (OCP) applies to real-world Angular development. In the next article, we’ll continue the series by exploring the Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) in Angular and see how it influences Angular architecture.
Thanks for reading, and I’ll see you in the next one.
